title: GA CVR Data Request (2022, 2024) (Sumter County Voter Registration And Elections)

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: GA CVR Data Request (2022, 2024) (Sumter County Voter Registration And Elections)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Cast vote record (CVR) data for the following elections:
1. 2022 Nov Midterm Election
2. 2024 Nov General Election

Specifically, I’m looking for the full anonymized record of votes cast each election generated by the Dominion voting system. Forsyth County has an example of these records posted for the 2024 General Election under the name “Cast Vote Records (CVR) Report” at this link: https://www.forsythco.com/Departments-Offices/Voter-Registrations-Elections/Election-Results. Please let me know if you need any further clarification on the type of data that I am requesting.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Aleksandra Conevska

title: communications & agreements – Cybercheck

communications.subject: Pennsylvania Right to Know Act Request: communications & agreements – Cybercheck
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Pennsylvania Right to Know Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) All agreements (contracts, licenses, MOUs, MOAs, data agreements, letters of intent, State of Work documents, Scope of Work documents, and other agreement documents) made since Dec. 1, 2024 between the Allegheny County District Attorney Office and Global Intelligence Inc. (also called Cybercheck or Cybercheck.AI) for the provision of the Cybercheck service.

2) All email exchanges, including attachments, between the Allegheny County District Attorney Office's staff and email addresses with the domain "@cybercheck.ai" between July. 1, 2023 and the present.

3) All emails, including attachments, exchanged between staff at the Allegheny County District Attorney's Office, that reference Cybercheck or its provider Global Intelligence, sent between Jan. 1, 2023 and the present. 

I kindly request that you waive all fees as I am a journalist and the requested records will be used for journalism in the public interest.

If you choose to impose fees, I request a detailed breakdown of the fees, including the hourly wage of each employee involved and an explanation of the employee hours required to fulfil the request.

If you choose to reject this request or redact portions of responsive documents, I ask that you provide a detailed breakdown of the statutory exemptions and associated case law underlying your decision to withhold each/any portions from public review.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jessica Hatcher

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

[cid:image001.png@01D9C623.0D3F7D80]

Regards,
Renee

title: Plans concerning reduction in budget for FY26 and RIF of workforce

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Plans concerning reduction in budget for FY26 and RIF of workforce
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1.) Information regarding plans created on or after January 20, 2025 to reduce the budget of NSF in financial year 2026 (FY26), including:

1a.) Internal reports, memorandums, meeting minutes, or directives generated or received by the National Science Board or the Office of the Director concerning reductions to the overall budget of NSF in FY26, created on or after January 20, 2025.

1b.) E-mails including attachments sent on or after January 20, 2025 broadly to all division directors, or to all division directors in a directorate, concerning reductions to the overall budget of NSF in FY26.

2.) Information regarding planned or executed layoffs (reduction in force processes or RIF) on or after January 20, 2025 at NSF, including:

2a.) Internal reports, memorandums, meeting minutes, or directives generated or received by the National Science Board or the Office of the Director regarding planned or executed layoffs at NSF, created on or after January 20, 2025.

2b.) E-mails including attachments sent on or after January 20, 2025 broadly to all division directors, or to all division directors in a directorate, regarding layoffs at the NSF or layoffs of division directors.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I am willing to pay fees regarding my request provided I have received information on the total charges. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Daisy McDonald

title: Request for Body Cam Footage of DUI Arrest Involving Ievgeniia Pinchuk

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Request for Body Cam Footage of DUI Arrest Involving Ievgeniia Pinchuk
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am writing to formally request access to the bodycam footage under the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) related to the DUI arrest of Ievgeniia Pinchuk on December 12, 2023.

Incident Details for Footage Retrieval:

Date: December 12, 2023
Location: Main Street, Bushnell, Florida
Suspect: Ievgeniia Pinchuk, 21
Incident Summary: Pinchuk was arrested after she allegedly parked her Honda Civic on railroad tracks, leading to a CSX locomotive slamming into her vehicle. She was reportedly walking near the crash site when Sumter County sheriff’s deputies apprehended her. Pinchuk was charged with DUI and parking on railroad tracks.
I am requesting copies of all body-worn camera footage from officers who responded to the scene and interacted with Pinchuk during her arrest.

I request the following:

Bodycam footage from all responding officers.
Any related dashcam footage if available.
Any additional audio or video footage related to the arrest.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Harun

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Request for Body Cam Footage of DUI Arrest Involving Ievgeniia Pinchuk
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

I wanted to follow up on the following Florida Sunshine Law request, copied below, and originally submitted on Feb. 23, 2025. Please let me know when I can expect to receive a response.

Thanks for your help, and let me know if further clarification is needed.

communications.subject: Mailed in request for Footage Retrieval - Pinchuk, I.
communications.communication:
To whom it may concern,

I sincerely apologize for the delay in my response to your mailed in requests. I understand that timely communication is important and I regret any inconvenience this may have caused. There have been an influx in requests due to our ransomware attack to the agencies computer system and I working diligently in answering all the request as best I can. Please see attached in response to your request.

Thank You for your patience!
Best Regards,


Vanessa Ramos
Records Clerk

Sumter County Sheriffs Office
7361 Powell Road
Wildwood, FL 34785
Tel # (352) 569-1600
Fax # (352) 569-1666
Vramos@sumterso.org

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Request for Body Cam Footage of DUI Arrest Involving Ievgeniia Pinchuk
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

I wanted to follow up on the following Florida Sunshine Law request, copied below, and originally submitted on Feb. 23, 2025. Please let me know when I can expect to receive a response.

Thanks for your help, and let me know if further clarification is needed.

Good Morning, 

The Sumter County Sheriff’s Office experienced a ransomware attack on August 1st,2024. As a result, we do not have access to the majority our records prior to August 1st.

If you can provide a case number we may be able to locate body worn camera (if applicable). We will not have any CAD data, incident reports, or other information if this occurred prior to our attack unless we previously pulled the case for someone else. Unfortunately, we cannot attempt to locate that data at all without a case number. 

We are working diligently towards a solution to this issue, however, cannot provide a date we expect total restoration. 

We appreciate your understanding and patience during this difficult and challenging time. 
 
Best Regards, 
Vanessa Ramos

title: ORT charges (San Diego County District Attorney)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: ORT charges (San Diego County District Attorney)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

From 1/1/2019-3/11/2025, for any case where any one of the following penal code
sections were charged: 490.4 (a), 459.5, 484(a) – (and whether the special
allegation of 490.2 was alleged), the following statistical information:
- Date of filing
- Additional charges
- Age of the defendant at the time of the crime
- Race/national origin/ethnicity
- Gender
- Outcome proceeding type + date
- Outcome (dismissal, sentence, etc)
- Amount of theft if entered in PIMS

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joey Scott
Please see the attached response letter and responsive record. This request is now closed.

communications.communication:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

All unedited body-worn camera / bodycam recordings related to the following law enforcement critical incident: 

Incident Date: August 6, 2023

Victim Name: Juan Leonard Johnson

I am specifically requesting the unedited body-worn camera recordings captured by all officers present for the full duration of the incident, including audio recordings associated with the footage.

Sincerely,

Jeffrey Lamson

title: Wayne County Opioid Settlement Fund Request

communications.subject: West Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Wayne County Opioid Settlement Fund Request
communications.communication:
Johnathan Edwards 
2040 University Avenue- Apartment 301
Morgantown, WV 26505

02/24/2025

Craig Evans
Wayne County Clerk
Clerk’s Office of Wayne County
700 Hendricks Street
Wayne, WV 25570

Dear Mr. Evans: 

Under the West Virginia Freedom of Information Act, §29-B-1-1 et seq., I am requesting an opportunity to inspect or obtain copies of public records that show the following; Allocation of opioid settlement funds received by Wayne County, the application that individuals or organizations seeking funding from the county complete, copies of grant applications from individuals or organizations that have been approved to receive these funds, the individuals who will review the funding applications, any meeting minutes of county-level officials where the receiving or distribution of county-level opioid settlement funding was discussed, and how much funding has been awarded as of March 1, 2025, and to whom it was awarded. If there are any fees for searching or copying these records, please inform me if the cost will exceed $25. However, I would also like to request a waiver of all fees in that the disclosure of the requested information is in the public interest and will contribute significantly to the public’s understanding of how this large sum of allocated funds is being distributed across the county. I am a student reporter at West Virginia University and intend to use this information to more accurately report on these findings. This information is not being sought for commercial purposes. The West Virginia Freedom of Information Act requires a response to this request be made within five business days. If access to the records I am requesting will take longer than this amount of time, please contact me with information about when I might expect copies or the ability to inspect the requested records. You can call me at 304-638-6367 or send me an email at jde00006@mix.wvu.edu My physical address is 2040 University Ave. Morgantown, WV, 26505.

title: Univ. of Illinois Libraries' ScienceDirect license agreement

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Univ. of Illinois Libraries' ScienceDirect license agreement
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act (5 ILCS 140), I hereby request the following records:

1. Most recent governing, base, or master license with Elsevier, a subsidiary of RELX, relating to the product ScienceDirect.
2. All related amendments, addenda, appendices, attachments, product terms, MOUs, MOAs, data processing agreements, letters of intent.
3. All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to the contractual relations with Elsevier’s ScienceDirect. Responsive materials include invoices, order forms, and any other documents that incorporate language governing terms of use of the ScienceDirect product.

Please do not limit your search to strictly direct agreements or renewals between the institution and Elsevier, but include all agreements and related documentation through consortia such as the Consortium of Academic and Research Libraries in Illinois (CARLI) or Lyrasis.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com.  I am affiliated with an educational research institution; this request is made for a scholarly purpose and not for a commercial use.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,
ekkd

communications.communication:
March 28, 2025

Via electronic mail
Unknown
MuckRock News
183732-58201212@requests.muckrock.com<mailto:183732-58201212@requests.muckrock.com>

Re: FOIA Request 25-457

Dear Sir or Madam:

      I am responding to your request dated and received in my office on March 21, 2025, under the Illinois Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) in which you requested:

                  “the following records:

1. Most recent governing, base, or master license with Elsevier, a subsidiary of RELX, relating to the product ScienceDirect.
2. All related amendments, addenda, appendices, attachments, product terms, MOUs, MOAs, data processing agreements, letters of intent.
3. All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to the contractual relations with Elsevier’s ScienceDirect. Responsive materials include invoices, order forms, and any other documents that incorporate language governing terms of use of the ScienceDirect product.

Please do not limit your search to strictly direct agreements or renewals between the institution and Elsevier, but include all agreements and related documentation through consortia such as the Consortium of Academic and Research Libraries in Illinois (CARLI) or Lyrasis.”

      I am writing to invoke an extension of the deadline for responding to the request under the following section(s) of the FOIA, which allows for additional time when:


  *   140/3(e)(iii) the request is couched in categorical terms and requires an extensive search for the records responsive to it.



  *   140/3(e)(vi) the request for records cannot be complied with by the public body within the time limits prescribed by paragraph (c) of this Section without unduly burdening or interfering with the operations of the public body.


      We are taking the additional five business days allowed by law to complete processing this request. The revised deadline will now be April 4, 2025.

Sincerely,

Adrienne Nazon
Vice President, External Relations and Communications
and Chief Records Officer

communications.subject: FOIA Request 25-457
communications.communication:
April 3, 2025

Via electronic mail
Unknown
MuckRock News
183732-58201212@requests.muckrock.com<mailto:183732-58201212@requests.muckrock.com>

Re: FOIA Request 25-457

Dear Sir or Madam:

      I am responding to your request dated and received in my office on March 21, 2025, under the Illinois Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) in which you requested:

                  “the following records:

1. Most recent governing, base, or master license with Elsevier, a subsidiary of RELX, relating to the product ScienceDirect.
2. All related amendments, addenda, appendices, attachments, product terms, MOUs, MOAs, data processing agreements, letters of intent.
3. All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to the contractual relations with Elsevier’s ScienceDirect. Responsive materials include invoices, order forms, and any other documents that incorporate language governing terms of use of the ScienceDirect product.

Please do not limit your search to strictly direct agreements or renewals between the institution and Elsevier, but include all agreements and related documentation through consortia such as the Consortium of Academic and Research Libraries in Illinois (CARLI) or Lyrasis.”

      Information responsive to your request is available. These are public records numbering 165 pages. Due to file size, the records referenced above are available for download at https://uofi.box.com/s/555cv0c0fnu5h74vp4fjgw9rd6q09eey. This link will expire in 10 business days. Because reading files in the Box interface can be slow and challenging, we suggest that you click the Download button to save your responsive file to your desktop.

   Portions of these records have been redacted pursuant to the following section(s) of the Act:


  *   140/7(1)(b) that exempts from disclosure “Private information, unless disclosure is required by another provision of this Act, a State or federal law or a court order.” This includes personal telephone numbers and signatures.

  *   140/7(1)(c) that exempts from disclosure “Personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which, if disclosed, would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subjects of the information.” This includes vendor customer account numbers and vendor banking information including bank name, account numbers, routing numbers and wire transfer numbers.

  *   140/7(1)(o) that exempts from disclosure “Administrative or technical information associated with automated data processing operations, including, but not limited to, software, operating protocols, computer program abstracts, file layouts, source listings, object modules, load modules, user guides, documentation pertaining to all logical and physical design of computerized systems, employee manuals, and any other information that, if disclosed, would jeopardize the security of the system or its data or the security of materials exempt under this Section.” This includes IP addresses.

  *   140/7(1)(kk) that exempts from disclosure “The public body’s credit card numbers, debit card numbers, bank account numbers, Federal Employer Identification Number, security code numbers, passwords, and similar account information, the disclosure of which could results in identity theft or impression or defrauding of a governmental entity or a person.” This includes the University’s Tax-Exempt Identification Number and SIS ID number.


      You have a right under the law to seek a review of this response by the Public Access Counselor (PAC) in the Office of the Attorney General. The PAC may be reached by phone at 877.299.3642 or by postal mail to Leah Bartelt, Public Access Counselor, Office of the Illinois Attorney General, 500 South 2nd Street, Springfield, Illinois 62701. You also have the right to seek judicial review under section 11 of this Act.

      If you have questions for our office, please contact 217-333-6400.

                                                                                                  Sincerely,

                                                                                                  Adrienne Nazon
                                                                                                  Vice President, External Relations and
                                                                                                  Communications
                                                                                                  and Chief Records Officer

Ben Welsh

title: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Public Records Request – Body-Worn Camera Footage of Mayor Teresa Heitmann DUI Arrest (August 28, 2024)

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Public Records Request – Body-Worn Camera Footage of Mayor Teresa Heitmann DUI Arrest (August 28, 2024)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

All unedited body-worn camera footage recorded by Collier County Sheriff’s Office deputies involved in the traffic stop, sobriety testing, and arrest of Mayor Teresa Heitmann following a reported DUI incident involving a damaged mailbox near her residence.

Dashcam footage from the officer who pulled her over regarding the events leading up to the suspect's arrest, capturing her sobriety tests.

The relevant 911 call which called officers to the scene.

This includes footage from the time deputies first made contact with Ms. Heitmann through her field sobriety test, arrest, and transport to the Naples Jail Center.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Police Cam News

title: Chief FOIA officer's recent email (U.S. Department of Education)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Chief FOIA officer's recent email (U.S. Department of Education)
communications.communication:
Dear U.S. Department of Education,

On behalf of myself and Fiat Fiendum, I hereby request the following records:

1. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's email inbox or equivalent which was received nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
2. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's email spam folder or equivalent which was received nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
3. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's sent email folder or equivalent which was sent nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
4. The total full-time equivalent count of people who work for your FOIA office as of October 19, 2024.

This request is expressly limited to U.S. Department of Education's own FOIA office. Please do not refer it to any other agency or division. This request is expressly not a Privacy Act request, and no PA waiver will be provided.

Please provide the email records in EML, Maildir, MBOX, MIX, MSG, or PST format only — not PDF, Word, image, etc — including all metadata (e.g. full email headers as received/sent) and attachments, without alteration other than narrowly tailored electronic redaction of specifically claimed exemptions that do not affect any part of non exempt information (and, in particular, without rasterization).

Please provide the fourth record as a statement in your response letter, or at your option, as the most readily available record, in original electronic format as currently stored on your computer systems, which includes that information.

Please provide all records either as individual files, or as an unencrypted ZIP file, uploaded to MuckRock. Do not apply any encryption, DRM, or other restriction.

I request fee waiver, because
* Fiat Fiendum is a 501(c)(3) non-profit;
* this request is for public interest, non-commercial purposes;
* these records would give a snapshot of insight into the everyday processes of FOIA offices; and
* these records are being requested in order to conduct a government-wide audit of agencies' FOIA compliance.

In the event that you deny fee waiver, please process this request as-is, because I will not agree to any fees.

Please be sure to provide:
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(II) FOIA Public Liaison information
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(III)(aa) appeal information
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(III)(bb) OGIS information
* 5 USC 552(a)(7)(A) tracking number
* 5 USC 552(a)(7)(B)(ii) completion ETA

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,
Sai
President, Fiat Fiendum, Inc.

P.S. Sai is my full legal name.

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Department of Education Letters to 60 Universities and Colleges (University of Massachusetts (Amherst))
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of the letter sent to your institution by the United States Department of Education on or about March 10, 2025, referencing Title VI. The letter is referenced in this press release: https://www.ed.gov/about/news/press-release/us-department-of-educations-office-civil-rights-sends-letters-60-universities-under-investigation-antisemitic-discrimination-and-harassment.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

The Massachusetts Public Records Law, M.G.L. Ch. 66, § 10, along with its associated regulations, permits the University to estimate and assess the estimated cost of searching for the requested records or segregating exempt information from non-exempt information.  I estimate that your request took less than four hours to complete and there will be no copying fee charged for this request.  As a result, there will be no fee.

Thank you,
Christine

title: OPRA Request – Full Bodycam & In-Car Footage: Liam Mahoney Arrest, Belmar Beach (August 20, 2024)

communications.subject: New Jersey Open Public Records Act Request: OPRA Request – Full Bodycam & In-Car Footage: Liam Mahoney Arrest, Belmar Beach (August 20, 2024)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Jersey Open Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I respectfully request the following records:

All body-worn camera footage from any Belmar Police Department officer involved in the encounter and arrest of Liam Mahoney on August 20, 2024, on the beach in Belmar, New Jersey. This request includes video from initial contact through the time Mr. Mahoney was placed into handcuffs at approximately 3:24 PM, and continuing through the conclusion of the incident, including any transport or field processing.

Any rear seat in-car video footage if Mr. Mahoney was placed in a patrol vehicle following his arrest.

This request is limited to footage directly related to Mr. Mahoney's arrest for obstruction, resisting arrest, and disorderly conduct. I understand bodycam footage has been publicly released in part; I request the complete, unedited footage for the full duration of officer interaction with Mr. Mahoney.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Police Cam News

communications.subject: OPRA Request
communications.communication:
We have received your Open Public Records Act Request. Please be advised
the Borough of Belmar now uses an online OPRA portal
https://belmarborough.nextrequest.com/. Your request will be uploaded into
this portal and you will receive an email confirmation. From there you can
finish creating your account so you can access your request. Your request
will be answered through this portal.* In the future please submit your
requests directly in the portal. *Thank you.

*Note: *Effective September 3, 2024, P.L. 2024, c. 16 requires all agencies
subject to OPRA to “adopt the form established by the Government Records
Council . . . for the use of any person who requests access to a government
record held or controlled by the public agency.” N.J.S.A. 47:1A-5(f).

 In accordance with this new requirement, the Government Records Council
(“GRC”) has established an updated version of the old "Model OPRA request
form" to include the following required items:

1) certifiable statements addressing commercial purpose and pending
litigation have been added to the “Requestor Information” box.

2) new and amended exemptions have been added to the “Reasons for Denial”
list, and

3) the information page has been changed to reflect relevant new and
amended provisions.

Requestors are not required to use an OPRA form, however, a written
equivalent not containing the form requirement of N.J.S.A 47:1A-5(f) and
N.J.S.A. 47:1A-5(g) may be denied by a custodian.
-- 

*April Claudio,* *RMC/CMC/CMR*
*Municipal Clerk/Registrar*
*Planning & Zoning Board Secretary*
*Technical Assistant to the Construction Official*

title: Public Records Request – Sabrina Coyne Arrest Footage (January 24, 2025 – Bonita Springs)

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Public Records Request – Sabrina Coyne Arrest Footage (January 24, 2025 – Bonita Springs)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting access to the following public records:

Body-worn camera footage from any deputy involved in the response and arrest of Sabrina Coyne on the evening of January 24, 2025, at or near the residence of Charles Kilo in Bonita Springs, FL, beginning at approximately 10:30 PM and concluding with the end of on-scene activity or transport.

Rear seat in-car camera footage, if Ms. Coyne was placed in a patrol vehicle following her arrest or detainment.

This request is specifically related to the incident where Ms. Coyne allegedly threw a brick through her ex-husband’s window and was uncooperative during questioning. The timeframe requested is limited to reduce burden and focuses only on video directly tied to this incident.

If necessary, I consent to redactions in accordance with Florida law and request the release of all non-exempt portions.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Police Cam News

title: FDLE State Exam Applicants

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: FDLE State Exam Applicants
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Information on all applicants who took the FDLE State Exam / State Officer Certification Examination going back as far as possible to the present. 

Data elements for all applicants:
* Applicant's full name
* Date of exam
* Applicant's date of birth or, if not releasable, year of birth or age at time of exam
* Applicant's city and/or zip code of residence at time of exam
* Applicant's score on the exam
* Whether applicant passed the exam

Please include this information for an applicant for as many times as they took the exam. If your certification system contains data elements not listed above, please include them in the response, provided they are releasable under the law. On the other hand, I recognize some of the information I am asking for may not be tracked by your system. If that is the case, I am willing to accept as many of the data elements as your agency maintains. If some records are more readily available, I am happy to receive partial information as soon as possible while the remaining request is processed.

In addition to the data elements listed, I request documentation necessary to understand and interpret the data, including but not limited to record layouts, data dictionaries, code sheets, lookup tables, etc.

My preference is to receive structured data provided in a csv file. I can also handle a variety of other data formats including machine-readable text files, such as delimited or fixed-width formats, SQL databases, Excel workbooks and MS Access. If there are additional formats your agency would prefer to provide, please let me know.

Please send clarifications and questions via electronic communication at any time.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Aleksei Opacic

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

Thank you for contacting the Florida Department of Law Enforcement's Public Records Section. Your tracking number is PRR-2024-3441.

Public records requests are processed in the order that they are received. Processing time may be lengthy due to the nature and extent of the request. Searches may be negative and FDLE may not have records responsive to your public records request. You may also receive an invoice for your request depending on the nature and extent of your public records request. A copy of the FDLE Guide to Public Records is attached for your review.

Please be advised that FDLE may not be the custodian of all of the records you requested. FDLE is not the custodian of all State of Florida criminal incident-related records for every state and local criminal justice agency.

Additional information regarding how to obtain public records including what costs may be applicable may be found on our website http://www.fdle.state.fl.us/OGC/Public-Records.aspx.

We are committed to our fundamental values of Service, Integrity, Respect, and Quality.

Sincerely,

Office of Open Government - Public Records Section

Thank you for contacting the Florida Department of Law Enforcement Office of Open Government. This message is being provided as confirmation your message was received. You should receive a response to your inquiry as soon as possible.



If you need criminal history records, please visit our website, https://www.fdle.state.fl.us/Criminal-History-Records/Obtaining-Criminal-History-Information.aspx, and/or contact FDLE’s Criminal History Services Section at ApplicantChecks@fdle.state.fl.us<mailto:ApplicantChecks@fdle.state.fl.us> or (850) 410-8161.



Public records requests are processed in the order that they are received. Processing time may be lengthened due to the nature and extent of the request. Searches may be negative and FDLE may not have records responsive to your public records request. You may also receive an invoice for your request depending on the nature and extent of your public records request. Please feel free to contact us at (850) 410-7676, or publicrecords@fdle.state.fl.us<mailto:publicrecords@fdle.state.fl.us>, if you have additional specific information relating to the records you are requesting, as this may help expedite your request and/or reduce costs that may be associated with the request.



Additional information regarding how to obtain public records including what costs may be applicable is contained from the hyperlink below. We are committed to our fundamental values of Service, Integrity, Respect, and Quality.



For Additional Information click here: Open Government (state.fl.us)<https://www.fdle.state.fl.us/Open-Government>

title: Crime Incident Requests

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Crime Incident Requests
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting data on crime incidents—those classified by your agency as crimes—rather than calls for service or unfounded incidents.
• Year(s) Requested: 2010 and 2011
• Columns Requested: Incident date, Incident time, Type of crime (e.g., robbery, theft, etc.), Incident ID, and all other available columns that do not require additional processing by the agency or redaction.

If the data are stored in a proprietary or custom electronic format not publicly available, I request that it be converted to a format viewable with standard software, such as Microsoft Excel or CSV. Please avoid providing data in PDF or paper printouts.

This request is made to support academic research conducted in the public interest and is not for commercial purposes. The data will contribute to a research project assessing the effect of music concerts on crime, aiming to enhance public understanding of how large events influence community safety.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Kristina Block

title: Washington State Department of Social and Health Services - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Washington State Department of Social and Health Services - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024
communications.communication:
January 12, 2025

via email to "DSHS Public Disclosure" <DSHSPublicDisclosure@dshs.wa.gov>

Washington State Department of Social and Health Services - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024
 
To whom it may concern,

RCW 40.14.026(5)

“To improve best practices for dissemination of public records, each agency with actual staff and legal costs associated with fulfilling public records requests of at least one hundred thousand dollars during the prior fiscal year must… report to the joint legislative audit and review committee by July 1st of each subsequent year the following metrics, measured over the preceding year:

RCW 40.14.026(5)(l)

(l) The estimated costs incurred by the agency in fulfilling records requests, including costs for staff compensation and legal review, and a measure of the average cost per request;

RCW 40.14.026(5)(o)

(o) The costs incurred by the agency with managing and retaining records, including staff compensation and purchases of equipment, hardware, software, and services to manage and retain public records or otherwise assist in the fulfillment of public records requests;

PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST RCW 42.56

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act [RCW 42.56] I hereby request the following records:

1. Please provide all "Public Records" (as defined by WAC 44-14-03001) detailing costs incurred by your agency in fulfilling records requests, including staff compensation, legal review, and any public records related litigation costs and/or legal settlements for the year 2024 and complete copies of all records request realted fee payments paid to your agency in 2024.

Responsive public records should include but are not limited to:

Supplies and services external services (e.g., printing services, large format printing) Mailing costs, supplies (CDs, DVDs, USB sticks, etc.) Staff compensation and benefit records, copies of payments of Public Records Fees Collected, Software licensing, public records portal and database software licensing and costs, purchases of equipment, hardware, software, and services to manage and retain public records or otherwise assist in the fulfillment of public records requests, professional services Agency staff costs, copies of billing for all Legal costs – including copies of all litigation Legal settlements related to public records requests litigation of any kind and copies of costs for staff time associated with invoicing and collection.

RECORDS INSTALLMENTS

If production of responsive records will be completed in multiple installments, please begin by producing records in the numerical order requested by subject matter and year. The most recent public records should be produced first.

DEFINITION OF RECORDS AND WRITINGS

RECORDS AND WRITINGS as defined by RCW 42.56.010(4): any handwriting, typewriting, printing, photostating, photographing, and every other means of recording any form of communication or representation including, but not limited to, letters, words, pictures, sounds, or symbols, or combination thereof, and all papers, maps, magnetic or paper tapes, photographic films and prints, motion picture, film and video recordings, magnetic or punched cards, discs, drums, diskettes, sound recordings, and other documents including existing data compilations from which information may be obtained or translated.

PRODUCTION AND DELIVERY OF ELECTRONIC RECORDS

Please provide all records in their native electronic format. Please do not instead create new records by printing electronic files then scanning and printing the newly scanned prints.

The use of 3rd party “portals” (Such as GOVQA or NEXTREQUEST) for communication and production of records in response to a public records request is optional for the requestor in the State of Washington. Respectfully we decline to use any 3rd party "portal" system, specifically GOVQA and NEXTREQUEST. Please provide all records electronically via direct email attachment, or via no password, no registration internet cloud-based download link.

Please do not direct or invite us to use, register for, or communicate with your agency via any 3rd party portal including but not limited to FOIAOnline, GovQA, NextRequest, FOIAExpress, JustFOIA FOIADirect, WebForm, or any other commercial 3rd party records portal service.

Constructive Notice: Any and all communication(s) received on behalf of your agency in reference to this Public Records Request (RCW 42.45) from any unauthorized for-profit 3rd party company doing business outside the State of Washington will be the subject of a new public records request to your agency as to the origin and purpose of the communication as well as the identity of the sender of the communication.

PUBLIC RECORDS REQUESTS SUBMITTED VIA EMAIL

RCW 42.56.080 - Identifiable records—Facilities for copying—Availability of public records.

"...Agencies shall honor requests received in person during an agency's normal office hours, or by mail or email, for identifiable public records unless exempted by provisions of this chapter. No official format is required for making a records request; however, agencies may recommend that requestors submit requests using an agency provided form or web page."

This public records request is being made via email. This public records request will be honored and fulfilled by your agency via email as requested or relief will be sought per statute.

NATIVE ELECTRONIC FORMAT

Please provide all identified public records in their NATIVE electronic format. Unless the records exist IN PAPER FORM ONLY, DO NOT instead create new records by printing native stored electronic files, then scanning and re-printing these newly scanned prints only to reproduce them in again in electronic production.

EMAIL RECORDS

Please provide any and all email records in NATIVE .pst electronic format.

FEES

In the event that there are fees, please inform us of the total charges in advance of fulfilling the request in strict compliance with all provisions of the Washington State Public Records Act.

EXEMPTION - FAMILY EDUCATIONAL RIGHTS AND PRIVACY ACT (FERPA)

Take caution with the broad application of redaction and withholding of identified public records claiming "global FERPA" exemptions. When an agency claims an exemption for an entire record or portion of one, it must inform the requestor of the statutory exemption and provide a brief explanation of how the exemption applies to the record or portion withheld. RCW 42.17.310(4)/42.56.210(3). The brief explanation should cite the statute the agency claims grant an exemption from disclosure. The brief explanation should provide enough information for a requestor to make a threshold determination of whether the claimed exemption is proper. Global, nonspecific claims of exemption such as "FERPA" are insufficient. One way to properly provide a brief explanation of the withheld record or redaction is for the agency to provide a withholding index. It identifies the type of record, its date and number of pages, and the author or recipient of the record (unless their identity is exempt). The withholding index should allow a requestor to make a threshold determination of whether the agency has properly invoked the exemption. There are several exceptions to the FERPA exemption and any agency silently withholding large swaths of public records citing "FERPA!" without providing the original identified record, properly redacted, or if withheld in its entirety, providing a record description and page count or record length, will be challenged in accordance with RCW 42.56.550 if a reasonably detailed withholding index or exemption log is not included.

EXEMPTION LOGS

Please ensure all redactions or exemptions claimed by your agency in the production of responsive records are accompanied by a complete and detailed exemption log noting the valid legal reason for each exemption at each redaction location in the record produced, as well as the specific number of pages if any that your agency redacts or withholds in their entirety. Each redaction should be noted by footnote or by a clear reference to the specific justification for that redaction, and only the minimal exempt portion of any record may be withheld.

COMMERCIAL PURPOSE DECLARATION

The Washington State Public Records Act prohibits the disclosure of “lists of individuals” for a commercial purpose (RCW 42.56.070(8)). I declare this public records request is not being made for any commercial purpose whatsoever. Also, this public records request is not being made for a "list of individuals." This declaration satisfies all requirements of RCW 42.56 regarding prohibitions on lists and commercial purposes. No additional commercial purpose declaration will be completed for this public records request.

COMMUNICATION VIA EMAIL

Please send all requests for clarification, status updates, and production of responsive electronic documents via direct email.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. We look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Good Luck.

communications.subject: Regarding 202501 PRR 201
communications.communication:
Hello,
In response to the attached request (DSHS ID# 202501 PRR 201) we sent an email on March 24, 2025. The letter attached to the email provided the managed file transfer access details for an installment of records. In the letter I stated that if the installment was not retrieved by March 31, 2025, we would consider the request abandoned and it would be closed. I am sending this email to let you know that since the records were not retrieved by March 31, 2025, we consider the request closed.

Please contact me at your earliest convenience (and within 30 days) if in fact you are still interested in receiving records responsive to the attached request.

Please note that for security reasons our standard practice for providing records is not to utilize links provided by other parties. Our standard practice is to provide records by managed file transfer site, or by mailing a CD or a USB drive. If you are still interested in receiving records, please let me know which of these options you would prefer.

Sincerely,

Geoff  Nisbet / Public Records Officer & Information Governance Administrator
Office of Information Governance / Office of the Secretary
Washington State Department of Social and Health Services

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: SWAT Call Outs (Burbank Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to SWAT call-outs:
SWAT includes SEB or any similar division at your agency
Data recorded by the department into a database or in reports that have:
- the deployment reasons/nature of each SWAT call-out (mental health, barricaded suspect, assist with federal or local partners, etc)
- any use of force, including the use of tear-gas and explosive breaching rounds
- deployment of any specialized equipment (drones, MRAPs)
- conclusion of call 
- dates
I don't need information on the who of the investigations; I need the what (use of force, specialized equipment) and why (deployment reason, conclusion of call) of each deployment. 

Please keep in native .csv if it's from a database.

Search 2024

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joey Scott

communications.subject: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: FRS Reports (Virginia Military Institute)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I request the NCAA Membership Financial Reporting System revenue and expense reports for fiscal (or reporting) years 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019, 2020, 2021, 2022, 2023 & 2024. Specifically:

These reports are completed by the athletic department for the National Collegiate Athletic Association for the fiscal years listed above. This report is a multi-page document that had to be submitted to the NCAA in January. It contains 40+ revenue and expense categories, followed by specific breakdowns of each of those categories, by sport and gender. I am requesting the full report, including the detail tables, the “Other Reporting Items” list and the “Statement of Revenues and Expenses” that appears at the end of the report. PLEASE NOTE: The NCAA report is different than the equity report that is sent to the U.S. Department of Education for Title IX compliance.

I prefer to receive the records electronically as an Adobe Acrobat (.pdf) file.

If you choose to deny this request, please provide a written explanation for the denial including a reference to the specific statutory exemption(s) on which you rely. Also, please provide all segregable portions of otherwise exempt material.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tom Nash, a citizen of Virginia, in coordination with Stacey Brook.

title: Black (African) Book Publishers, Distributors, Stores, Authors and/or Titles

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Black (African) Book Publishers, Distributors, Stores, Authors and/or Titles
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

In October 1968, J. Edgar Hoover and the FBI (All Field Offices) launched a COINTELPRO Operation against black independent bookstores (booksellers), associations, distributors, publishers, authors, titles, etc. It was modeled after similar operations since the 1920s against independent, radical, leftist, socialist, communist, and other bookstores (booksellers), associations, distributors, publishers, authors, titles, etc.

Each FBI Office and Sub-Office was required to (1) identify bookstores in their territory, and (2) open investigations on each to determine if it was extremist in nature,” (3) the identities of the owners; (4) whether it is a front for any group or foreign interest; (5) whether individuals affiliated with the store engage in extremist activities; (5) the number, type, and source of books and material on sale; (5) the store’s financial condition; (6) its clientele; and (7) whether it is used as a headquarters or meeting place.”

We are especially interested about books by and about Kwame Nkrumah and Panaf Books (Press), Sekou Toure, Malcolm X, Marcus Garvey, Mao Tse Tung

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

ROBERT BROWN

Per Gov. Code, § 12525.5(d):

State and local law enforcement agencies shall not report the name, address, social security number, or other unique personal identifying information of persons stopped, searched, or subjected to a property seizure, for purposes of this section. title: NORTH THURSTON SCHOOL DISTRICT - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: NORTH THURSTON SCHOOL DISTRICT - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024
communications.communication:
January 12, 2025

via email to publicrecords@nthurston.k12.wa.us

NORTH THURSTON SCHOOL DISTRICT - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024
 
To whom it may concern,

RCW 40.14.026(5)

“To improve best practices for dissemination of public records, each agency with actual staff and legal costs associated with fulfilling public records requests of at least one hundred thousand dollars during the prior fiscal year must… report to the joint legislative audit and review committee by July 1st of each subsequent year the following metrics, measured over the preceding year:

RCW 40.14.026(5)(l)

(l) The estimated costs incurred by the agency in fulfilling records requests, including costs for staff compensation and legal review, and a measure of the average cost per request;

RCW 40.14.026(5)(o)

(o) The costs incurred by the agency with managing and retaining records, including staff compensation and purchases of equipment, hardware, software, and services to manage and retain public records or otherwise assist in the fulfillment of public records requests;

PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST RCW 42.56

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act [RCW 42.56] I hereby request the following records:

1. Please provide all "Public Records" (as defined by WAC 44-14-03001) detailing costs incurred by your agency in fulfilling records requests, including staff compensation, legal review, and any public records related litigation costs and/or legal settlements for the year 2024 and complete copies of all records request realted fee payments paid to your agency in 2024.

Responsive public records should include but are not limited to:

Supplies and services external services (e.g., printing services, large format printing) Mailing costs, supplies (CDs, DVDs, USB sticks, etc.) Staff compensation and benefit records, copies of payments of Public Records Fees Collected, Software licensing, public records portal and database software licensing and costs, purchases of equipment, hardware, software, and services to manage and retain public records or otherwise assist in the fulfillment of public records requests, professional services Agency staff costs, copies of billing for all Legal costs – including copies of all litigation Legal settlements related to public records requests litigation of any kind and copies of costs for staff time associated with invoicing and collection.

RECORDS INSTALLMENTS

If production of responsive records will be completed in multiple installments, please begin by producing records in the numerical order requested by subject matter and year. The most recent public records should be produced first.

DEFINITION OF RECORDS AND WRITINGS

RECORDS AND WRITINGS as defined by RCW 42.56.010(4): any handwriting, typewriting, printing, photostating, photographing, and every other means of recording any form of communication or representation including, but not limited to, letters, words, pictures, sounds, or symbols, or combination thereof, and all papers, maps, magnetic or paper tapes, photographic films and prints, motion picture, film and video recordings, magnetic or punched cards, discs, drums, diskettes, sound recordings, and other documents including existing data compilations from which information may be obtained or translated.

PRODUCTION AND DELIVERY OF ELECTRONIC RECORDS

Please provide all records in their native electronic format. Please do not instead create new records by printing electronic files then scanning and printing the newly scanned prints.

The use of 3rd party “portals” (Such as GOVQA or NEXTREQUEST) for communication and production of records in response to a public records request is optional for the requestor in the State of Washington. Respectfully we decline to use any 3rd party "portal" system, specifically GOVQA and NEXTREQUEST. Please provide all records electronically via direct email attachment, or via no password, no registration internet cloud-based download link.

Please do not direct or invite us to use, register for, or communicate with your agency via any 3rd party portal including but not limited to FOIAOnline, GovQA, NextRequest, FOIAExpress, JustFOIA FOIADirect, WebForm, or any other commercial 3rd party records portal service.

Constructive Notice: Any and all communication(s) received on behalf of your agency in reference to this Public Records Request (RCW 42.45) from any unauthorized for-profit 3rd party company doing business outside the State of Washington will be the subject of a new public records request to your agency as to the origin and purpose of the communication as well as the identity of the sender of the communication.

PUBLIC RECORDS REQUESTS SUBMITTED VIA EMAIL

RCW 42.56.080 - Identifiable records—Facilities for copying—Availability of public records.

"...Agencies shall honor requests received in person during an agency's normal office hours, or by mail or email, for identifiable public records unless exempted by provisions of this chapter. No official format is required for making a records request; however, agencies may recommend that requestors submit requests using an agency provided form or web page."

This public records request is being made via email. This public records request will be honored and fulfilled by your agency via email as requested or relief will be sought per statute.

NATIVE ELECTRONIC FORMAT

Please provide all identified public records in their NATIVE electronic format. Unless the records exist IN PAPER FORM ONLY, DO NOT instead create new records by printing native stored electronic files, then scanning and re-printing these newly scanned prints only to reproduce them in again in electronic production.

EMAIL RECORDS

Please provide any and all email records in NATIVE .pst electronic format.

FEES

In the event that there are fees, please inform us of the total charges in advance of fulfilling the request in strict compliance with all provisions of the Washington State Public Records Act.

EXEMPTION - FAMILY EDUCATIONAL RIGHTS AND PRIVACY ACT (FERPA)

Take caution with the broad application of redaction and withholding of identified public records claiming "global FERPA" exemptions. When an agency claims an exemption for an entire record or portion of one, it must inform the requestor of the statutory exemption and provide a brief explanation of how the exemption applies to the record or portion withheld. RCW 42.17.310(4)/42.56.210(3). The brief explanation should cite the statute the agency claims grant an exemption from disclosure. The brief explanation should provide enough information for a requestor to make a threshold determination of whether the claimed exemption is proper. Global, nonspecific claims of exemption such as "FERPA" are insufficient. One way to properly provide a brief explanation of the withheld record or redaction is for the agency to provide a withholding index. It identifies the type of record, its date and number of pages, and the author or recipient of the record (unless their identity is exempt). The withholding index should allow a requestor to make a threshold determination of whether the agency has properly invoked the exemption. There are several exceptions to the FERPA exemption and any agency silently withholding large swaths of public records citing "FERPA!" without providing the original identified record, properly redacted, or if withheld in its entirety, providing a record description and page count or record length, will be challenged in accordance with RCW 42.56.550 if a reasonably detailed withholding index or exemption log is not included.

EXEMPTION LOGS

Please ensure all redactions or exemptions claimed by your agency in the production of responsive records are accompanied by a complete and detailed exemption log noting the valid legal reason for each exemption at each redaction location in the record produced, as well as the specific number of pages if any that your agency redacts or withholds in their entirety. Each redaction should be noted by footnote or by a clear reference to the specific justification for that redaction, and only the minimal exempt portion of any record may be withheld.

COMMERCIAL PURPOSE DECLARATION

The Washington State Public Records Act prohibits the disclosure of “lists of individuals” for a commercial purpose (RCW 42.56.070(8)). I declare this public records request is not being made for any commercial purpose whatsoever. Also, this public records request is not being made for a "list of individuals." This declaration satisfies all requirements of RCW 42.56 regarding prohibitions on lists and commercial purposes. No additional commercial purpose declaration will be completed for this public records request.

COMMUNICATION VIA EMAIL

Please send all requests for clarification, status updates, and production of responsive electronic documents via direct email.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. We look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Good Luck.

communications.subject: NTPS records request #25-04
communications.communication:
Thank you for you submitting your request to North Thurston Public Schools. This letter serves as the District’s initial response to your request under RCW 42.56.520.

Pursuant to RCW 42.56.520, the District is notifying you that additional time is required to respond to your request. This additional time is necessary to locate records that may be responsive to your request and, if so, to determine whether any exemptions might apply to those records.

Our initial estimate is that records may be available as soon as February 26, 2026. This anticipated date is only an estimate and may need to be revised as we process your request.  We will make every reasonable effort to respond as promptly as possible to your request.

The time required to respond to your request is based on the nature of your request and the number of other requests the District is currently handling, the need to locate and assemble the records requested, to notify third persons affected by your request, and/or to determine whether any of the requested information is exempt from public disclosure.
It is District policy to charge the following for producing records: $0.15 per page for photocopied or printed documents, $0.10 per page scanned into an electronic format, $0.05 per each four pages of electronic records produced electronically, $0.10 per GB for copies of digital files (including video), and the actual cost of any storage device, delivery charge, or postage. If the District will be charging you a fee to produce records responsive to your request, we will notify you of the fees owed and will produce the responsive records upon receipt of payment.

Sincerely,
North Thurston Public Schools
Public Records
360-412-4418
publicrecords@nthurston.k12.wa.us<mailto:publicrecords@nthurston.k12.wa.us>

Sincerely,

communications.communication:
North Thurston Public Schools (“District”) has completed its search for records responsive to your request.

Your files are available by clicking on the following link to download the files:

https://transfer.nthurston.k12.wa.us/message/ZVBRhqqhGeMInpJn7gsNhg

The attachments are available until: May 02, 2025

The District waives all fees for this request due to the low number of records produced. Your request is now considered closed, and this is the District’s final response to your request.

The records provided are fully responsive to your request as we have interpreted it, and your request is considered fully satisfied and will be closed as of today’s date without any further action. Pursuant to RCW 42.56.550, any judicial review of the district’s actions taken or challenged must be filed within one year of today’s date, April 2, 2025. If you have any questions or feel we have misinterpreted your request in any way, please contact NTPS at your earliest convenience so we can work together to resolve any issues.

Sincerely,

North Thurston Public Schools

title: Cook County Medical Examiner 2002 Deaths

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Cook County Medical Examiner 2002 Deaths
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

A log of all deaths recorded in Cook County in 2002, including but not limited to the following fields:
- First and last name of the deceased,
- Date of death,
- Date of birth,
- Address,
- Cause of death.

I preemptively agree to forego all sensitive private information such as social security numbers. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. I am a freelance reporter for Medill News and I am requesting this information in that editorial capacity.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled in the form of CSV or Excel file, and electronically by e-mail attachment if available.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Maggie Dougherty

title: Cybercheck communications and agreements

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Cybercheck communications and agreements
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) All contracts, licenses, MOUs, MOAs, data agreements, letters of intent, State of Work documents, Scope of Work documents, and other agreement documents since Jan. 1, 2024 between Yakima County Sheriff's Office and Global Intelligence Inc. (also called Cybercheck or Cybercheck.AI) for the provision of the Cybercheck service (excluding any already undisclosed via previous FOIAs).

2) All email exchanges, including attachments, between Yakima County Sheriff's Office staff and email addresses with the domain "@cybercheck.ai" between Jan. 1, 2024 and the present (excluding any already undisclosed via previous FOIAs).

3) All email exchanges, including attachments, between staff of Yakima County Sheriff's Office referencing Cybercheck or its provider Global Intelligence, sent between Jan. 1, 2023 and the present. 

I kindly request that you waive all fees as I am a journalist and the requested records will be used for journalism in the public interest.

If you choose to impose fees, I request a detailed breakdown of the fees, including the hourly wage of each employee involved and an explanation of the employee hours required to fulfil the request.

If you choose to reject this request or redact portions of responsive documents, I ask that you provide a detailed breakdown of the statutory exemptions and associated case law underlying your decision to withhold each/any portions from public review.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jessica Hatcher
